{"cursor":"5822","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Formal semantics}}\n\nIn linguistics, 'formal semantics' seeks to understand linguistic meaning by\nconstructing precise mathematical models of the principles that speakers use to\ndefine relations between expressions in a natural language and the world which\nsupports meaningful discourse. , chapter 15: An Introduction to Formal\nsemantics.\n\nThe mathematical tools used are the confluence of formal logic and formal\nlanguage theory, especially typed lambda calculi.\n\nLinguists rarely employed formal semantics until Richard Montague showed how\nEnglish (or any natural language) could be treated like a formal\nlanguage. For a very readable and succinct overview of how formal semantics\nfound its way into linguistics, please refer to\n[https://www.msu.edu/~abbottb/formal.htm The formal approach to meaning: Formal\nsemantics and its recent developments] by Barbara Abbott. In: Journal of Foreign\nLanguages (Shanghai), 119:1 (January 1999), 2â20. His contribution to\nlinguistic semantics, which is now known as Montague grammar, was the basis for\nfurther developments, like the categorial grammar of Bar-Hillel and colleagues,\nand the more recent type-logical semantics (or grammar) based on Lambek\ncalculus.\n\nAnother line of inquiry, using linear logic, is Glue semantics, which is based\non the idea of \"interpretation as deduction\", closely related to the \"parsing as\ndeduction\" paradigm of categorial grammar.\n\nIn 1992 Margaret King argued that few of the proposals from formal semanticists\nhave been tested for empirical relevance, unlike those in computational\nlinguistics.\n\nCognitive semantics emerged and developed as a reaction against formal\nsemantics.\n","linknr":153,"url":"Formal_semantics_(linguistics)","recorded":1374860730,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Formal_semantics_(linguistics)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Formal_semantics_(linguistics)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/fa